<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-195-186 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 519 622</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  March 25 1991 n413 pS20(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's in a supplier: large and small companies have the sameanswer. (Benchmarks computer industry report on Desktops andLaptops)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Tami.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>MIS managers at larger or smaller companies both know thatanything a microcomputer can do for a big business it can do for asmaller one.andP;  This is why they think alike when it comes tochoosing microcomputer suppliers.andP;  A poll by the GallupOrganization shows that MIS managers seek the same qualities insuppliers and flock to and from those suppliers at the same time.andO;Service tops the list of desirable characteristics.andP;  Similaremphasis is placed on price, reputation, support and training, andproximity to company headquarters.andP;  However, productavailability/delivery time, central purchasing agreements andavailability of different brands matter more to larger companiesthan smaller ones.andP;  The road to locating acceptable service, forsome MIS managers, has been difficult.andP;  This is especially true ofthose who began with minicomputers and depended on the vendors tomaintain their systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Gallup Organization Inc. (Surveys).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersVendor RelationsMISManagementMarket AnalysisSurvey.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Primary sources, what they want from desktop suppliers. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>